Package ohos.event.commonevent

Class CommonEventData

  • java.lang.Object
    • ohos.event.commonevent.CommonEventData
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Sequenceable

    public final class CommonEventData
extends Object
implements Sequenceable
    Carries common events, for example, publishing common event contents and storing common events received after subscription.

    To publish a common event, call the CommonEventData(ohos.aafwk.content.Intent) or CommonEventData(ohos.aafwk.content.Intent,int,java.lang.String) method to initialize the Intent attribute, set Action and IntentParams of the common event based on Intent, and then use the CommonEventManager#publishCommonEvent(CommonEventData) method with CommonEventData as the input parameter to finish the publishing. To subscribe to a common event, you need to inherit the class CommonEventSubscriber and override the CommonEventSubscriber#onReceiveEvent(CommonEventData) callback method. After a common event is received, CommonEventData stores the received common event object.

    Since:
    1

      • CommonEventData

        public CommonEventData​(Intent intent,
                       int code,
                       String data)
        Creates a CommonEventData instance based on the parameters intent, code, and data to set the content of the common event.
        Parameters:
        intent - Indicates the Intent object used to set the common event content. This parameter is mandatory.
        code - Indicates the custom result code of the common event. The value of code is generally -1. You can set it to any int value. This parameter is only applicable to ordered common events and is optional.
        data - Indicates the custom result data of the common event. The value of data is generally null. You can set it to any character string. This parameter is only applicable to ordered common events and is optional.
        Since:
        1
        See Also:
        Intent

        public String toString​()
        Description copied from class: Object
        Returns a string representation of the object. In general, the toString method returns a string that "textually represents" this object. The result should be a concise but informative representation that is easy for a person to read. It is recommended that all subclasses override this method.

        The toString method for class Object returns a string consisting of the name of the class of which the object is an instance, the at-sign character `@', and the unsigned hexadecimal representation of the hash code of the object. In other words, this method returns a string equal to the value of: 

         getClass().getName() + '@' + Integer.toHexString(hashCode())
